{"key":"processedPost-10858284","value":{"id":10858284,"first":10840214,"last":10864015,"when":1250262677,"utime":"08/14/09 06:11 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><b>BrandNewbie said:</b><br />If you suspect a contaminate, try gently wiping a blue area with a moistened q-tip. If it's a mold it will wipe off. If it doesn't wipe off just leave it alone. <br /></blockquote><br /><br />The q-tip test was debunked years ago.&nbsp; It doesn't work.&nbsp; Mold spores will often not rub off and bruised mycelium often will, giving a false reading.&nbsp; This is at least the 100th time I've typed this.&nbsp; It's extremely easy to tell mold spores from bruising.&nbsp; Mold sits on the surface, while bruising is the color of the mycelium itself.<br /><br />That's bruising.&nbsp; Either you've handled your cakes too much, or they're dry.&nbsp; Pick them up to test for weight.&nbsp; If they're light, dunk them overnight.&nbsp; If not, they're fine.<br />RR","title":"Re: Blue/Purplish peaks...Is this bad? (Pics)","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}